The government wants to reduce the torture of "witches", published a brochure.
In Burkina Faso, women who have been declared witches share common traits.
Rather, they are part of the older generation, cannot work for health reasons, are free and have no children.
The one who becomes a "witch" is isolated so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"Man very rarely has this destiny."
“Young healthy women are not judged either because they are involved in labor and have children,” said a sister who works in the West African country’s capital, Burkina Faso, in a special facility of more than 100 women who have been rejected by society.
The local government has decided to intervene against this unusual "social measure".
He has published a booklet that is supposed to help limit witch hunting.
The case has a "hic".
