Households will pay a surcharge of a hundred crowns per month for housing.
Households will have to pay a surcharge from January onwards not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rentals will also increase.
As of January, families will have to pull up to a hundred kronor a month more than they now have.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some locations you will have to pay up to a tenth more water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity for households in apartments is expected to be around 100 crowns a year more than currently.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the sensitive development to encourage the production of renewable energy, especially photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the most consumption.
It is also possible to count an additional hundred crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating varies from city to city.
These are mainly the largest municipalities that plan to increase prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 more crowns per month for central heating as of January, and families in Libérec will pay more than 1000 crowns annually.
For residents of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change, the Pragoi will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
Rental prices will increase significantly in the 450,000 apartments rented from January onwards, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns nearly 2,500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase it to 100 percent.
Those who will not agree with the new increase in rents will be brought before the courts by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whiskey are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in the hospital for relapse are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to the admissions of the children's departments of hospitals.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk.”
"The trend is really strong alcohol," says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at the Horovice hospital in central Bohemia.
“When they manage to chip a bottle of dad in the cupboard, it’s sometimes whiskey but it’s the fernet and vodka that prevail.”
"Vodka has the advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it," explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, also gives him reason.
"In general, it's rum or Fernet."
"It's now fashionable alcohol, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought home," Jurinova added.
According to the Pelikan Department Head, seeing drunk children aged thirteen to fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was at Motol where he practiced pediatrics for ten years, where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the vast surroundings who were completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized like this four times.
"She started her career at twelve when she was brought up with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in her blood with an additional mix with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was away for 48 hours," said the Department Director.
It is precisely the disinterest of the parents or their extraordinary tolerance to the fact that their rejections indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of children's alcoholism.
According to specialists, however, we are not talking about dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
"The alcoholic vocabulary means a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that are not found in children."
"For those who use alcohol repeatedly, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-family background," Pelikan said.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are taken home after emergency care by their parents or the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, it excites, according to Pelikan, three seasonal waves with which one can count: Witch's Day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink despite poor results or they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course, I lived on Witch's Day an admission of seven drunken children at once," Pelikan said.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "wooden cheek".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They're better off because they're having a great evening and then a gentle awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re just amazed at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils patients’ mood at least with the grade to pay for their care.
Transportation by ambulance and hospitalization on intensive care beds can go up to tens of thousands of crowns.
“Occasionally, I applied this as a means of education by telling these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer working seasonally to pay off a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, he said, health insurance companies in their regressive management, which should recover care-related charges from parents, do not deal with cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain.
Two out of five L-159 aircraft, for which the Ministry of Defense traded Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday to Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were until now in service in the Czech army and were in flight.
The remaining Lestrois units are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the Vodochody aircraft is currently unknown.
The L-159 single-seater aircraft scheduled for exchange were taken on long-stocked aircraft without causing additional charges or investments for the Department of Defense.
"The two-seater L-159 T1 has been exchanged in the state," he told Pravo Pejsek.
He assured that the army will not remain without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, the second being scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek, EADS is committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of certain Alliance countries.
"In the contract it is clearly stated that the L-159 is EADS and that it will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries."
"It is therefore the business of the one who is considering how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced, some time ago, that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
