The Department of Defense did not call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
The defense management argued that the exchange ensures future exports of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and only used 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have judicial implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected as part of a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than the annular are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before age 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, notably by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index of the right hand shorter than the annular one.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the longer index than the annular the risk, however, fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60 the risk reduction reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two cited fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
A less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he was aware of the study but that it did not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "completely demonstrated".
