A microbe tolerant of arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, widens the field to find new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a dual capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
“That’s why it’s very special, even though it’s far from being a truly ‘foreign’ form of life,” said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday’s online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“We wonder what’s still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms may be able to use other elements to trigger biochemistry and that the "standard" set of elements, which we deem absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Scientific Research, Planetary, Kingdom Key, Open University, United States.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It was not a coincidental discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances might be able to substitute for each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms find it difficult to distinguish these elements separately."
"But arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow gums the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar said.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of Earth's existence, she says; so, researchers hypothesized that early life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways to shape life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
The last two stolen exhibition dogs were found in Compton
The other two exhibit dogs on four thefts from outside a Bellflower motel have been found, Los Angeles County Sheriffs announced Thursday.
The four show dogs - two Akitas and two Welsh pembroke corgis - disappeared Tuesday when someone stole the Chevrolet Express van in which they spent the night outside a Bellflower 6 motel, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two were found late Wednesday evening, Los Angeles County Sheriff Department spokesman Steve Whitmore said.
“The good news is that dogs are fine,” Whitmore says.
"They're in good shape."
"They have been returned to their legitimate owners."
Whitmore refused to say exactly where the dogs had been found, in what neighborhood and what were the circumstances of their discovery.
"An investigation is underway."
“We don’t want to say it,” Whitmore said.
"We're following orders."
The dog owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be joined to provide a comment on Thursday.
They met Wednesday afternoon with their two Akitas in a county animal shelter located in Downey.
The sheriff's deputies found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
The Akitas — Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female — were healthy and safe, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, the corgis that Rickard and Peek had planned to show at regional competitions this week, on behalf of the owners of the Japanese dogs, were missing until their discovery on Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend as part of the Long Beach AKC/Eukanuba National Championship, where they planned to introduce Trace.
The other dogs were expected to compete in other events scheduled in the days leading up to the "AKC/Eukanuba" exhibition, Peek told the Times on Wednesday.
South California is one of the stops on the couple’s nearly a month-long dog show tour.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van outside, right next to their bedroom window.
They took three other dogs - a Boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier and a Breton spaniel - who stayed with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and corgis, with thicker fur, in the van where it would be cooler.
They have a little open the windows, so that the dogs can have fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van was stolen at 6:00 a.m. on Tuesday.
Peek said they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the corgis, equipped with an implanted microchip to identify them.
It is unclear if a prize was awarded on Thursday.
The lion is ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is only waiting for the final green light of the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York on Thursday officially rented out the creditors' "pre-packed" plan that would wipe out about $5 billion of the debt; paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and television shows.
With Thursday’s decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, there is no longer any legal hurdle before MGM to reboot under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the CEOs of what will be a light studio.
Staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 at the start.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has completed a $500 million credit facility to fund MGM's new operations and productions.
It is currently distributed under license by the investment bank, which is running itself at $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The studio's restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances as it did not have the means to pay interest of $300 million per year.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and a recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to solve MGM’s financial hardships and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed, at the end of 2009, to put the company on sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the additional $2 billion the creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be reworked as the MGM team began working on a restructuring plan that, after months of disagreement and internal debate, was finally approved by the creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially comes out of bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper receive multimillion-dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper’s companies, who raised $375,000 a month for their company management services, will receive a “successful premium” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plans to relaunch the production of MGM, which released only one film this year, and build an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released from 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", with Warner Bros.
The studio is to conclude a separate loan between $265,000,000 and $275 million to finance its share in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who holds about 18% of MGM’s debt, has attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the main shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not led to an agreement.
