Prosecutors will not indict Senator Ensign
Prosecutors at the Justice Department have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign in a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get a job lobbying for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a potential Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case hits the national headlines last year and hurts his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Department of Justice had "informed Senator Ensign that he was no longer under investigation and that he had no intention of maintaining any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice abstained from commenting on the matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the case with her husband.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an associate of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law for one year from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to contradict the so-called ban on lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and materially violate the law of the swing gate," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning leading to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level backlashes filed by his department's public integrity senator, including last year's follow-up decisions.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the director-general of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's chief lawyer, said in an interview that he had received a phone call Monday from a prosecutor at the Justice Department and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to convince them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, “had acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutor's office.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, alleging that the $96,000 payment by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Department of the Interior on a disputed issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after he hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as a fourth-rank Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to contest a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Department of Justice's lead and end his investigation.
Senator Ensign is delighted to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
Cheshire's appeal will point to Twitter
About half a dozen of them were tapping away in the rows of the courtroom.
They sent every minute of the horrific testimonies via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said there were more than 140,000 messages about the rape case trial and the children tied to their bed in a house that was burned down.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to lead to an official end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted by the jury.
But Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that outlines appeals, likely to occupy the courts for years.
What’s provocative is that the intense reporting on the trial — as well as the widespread and widespread use by Twitter journalists — has created a “circus atmosphere,” a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the jury has been badly influenced by the public’s passions.
The request could prompt appellate judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in courtrooms.
“I experienced it in this trial; I think there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtrooms is undermining the human rights of a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, attorney for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. Bleue of the State Superior Court, laconically dismissed the claims in the ruling last week, claiming that the media was "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But that does not seem to be the last word on the matter.
The Courts of Appeal have recognized for decades that media coverage of notorious cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, arguing in his ruling that there was a “carnival atmosphere at trial” because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the TV show and the film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers have said that the appeals courts seized to review half a century later Mr. Hayes' conviction may be curious given the argument that new rules may be needed to manage the media of the courtrooms, unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is a general reason to worry about the impact of the new media" in large-scale trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily enforced.
Professor Donohue claims that some appellate judges may be intrigued by the idea that limiting instant communication from courtrooms could allow for more fair trials.
The case of Twitter is just one of many others described by Hayes’ lawyers, likely to be discussed for years; which delays execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Mr. Hayes suffered damage when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them macabre photos of criminal scenes when selecting the jury.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers claim that they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the jurors, who had been critical in front of prosecutors, and that he abusively put pressure on a verdict by taking the unusual decision to bring a judge to trial.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the biggest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and was being discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the United States Senate.
They maintained that the computer media continued to ignite the flames of the emotion of the case.
“The daily buzz of media, camera and journalist tweets in front of the courthouse,” the lawyers wrote, “wasn’t anything like what had been seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even nationally.”
Their focus on coverage of the Twitter system is controversial.
In the interviews, some journalists said that the claim that the news snapshots were more incendiary than the releases delivered more slowly was a ludicrous view that would impoverish the Court's policy of media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said appeals courts were often attracted by arguments that social and technological changes required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayes' lawyers insist on this claim.
In their file, they refer to the 1966 Supreme Court decision that overturned Dr. Sheppard's conviction because of the trial's media coverage and they specified that they would invoke the need for new rules for the new media.
"This case," they wrote, "represents that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can civility bring cleavages closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a forerunner of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the swift return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders has produced no breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the “lazy duck” session.
But obviously there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the Committee on the President’s Deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interplay of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a period of mutual testing and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments from the participants revealed a minimum of requirements or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, expenses, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then they disappear.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the "duck duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of it.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is envisaged on extending unemployment benefits, even though Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism floats over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lazy duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will come back to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civilization would lead to true cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the electorate present at the tea which contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to be up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the early responses to the recommendations of the Committee on the Deficit, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, according to them, imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have had a hard time reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group; this suggests that there are few reasons or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fights between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes, and health care; followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then the two parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who is judged to be a loser will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Revealed U.S. documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a “kleptocracy” and passes through to the Kremlin some of the bribes and protection money it collects, the U.S. embassy in Russia said in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are carrying out massive rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They are raising money not only from legitimate companies but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the “vertical of power” – takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The service note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been purged.
It was written while Yuri Loujkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but since then there has been little sign of cleansing.
Loujkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have always denied allegations of corruption over the years; and he has won several defamation trials on these allegations.
In September, he said the following to a Russian TV channel when questioned on a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's thrown, it's anything."
The Russians believe, in an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information stated in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be for diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the Moscow City government and the crime has led some people to call it “dysfunctional” and to claim that the government functioned more like a kleptocracy than a government, according to the embassy note.
"Criminal elements enjoy a "krysha" (the term used in the criminal world/mafia which literally means "roof" or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the government of the city of Moscovo.
"Analysts identify a three-level structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militias are at the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas where the city does not provide certain services."
The report indicates that the FSB is bribing the money of the largest companies and that the police are targeting the small ones.
A source, he said, "explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and the FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by it."
“That’s why the demand for protection from criminal gangs is no longer as high.”
The note notes that although the collection of money is extensive, the protection itself may be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their affairs shut down under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has repeatedly referred to the fight against corruption but admitted little progress.
The embassy note transmits reports of men bringing suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats," said in a recent interview Gueorgui Satarov, director of Moscow's Indem think tank.
"But he's part of this bureaucracy."
"It is not part of a political class because it does not exist in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the cost of corruption would rise, across Russia, to more than $300 billion a year.
The country was ranked 154th in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked at least the most corrupt).
The disclosure of the note from the US embassy, which was made only yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, will certainly stir discontent within the Russian government; although Loujkov may be blamed, to some extent, for the failures of Moscow, this could be the opportunity for the Kremlin to show that the train is in trouble.
Interviewed by CNN by Larry King, Putin hypothesized that WikiLeaks documents could be a fabrication and reacted with anger to what U.S. diplomats had revealed by calling him Batman and bringing Medvedev closer to Robin.
"The problem is that this is our interaction, an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he said.
“But to be honest with you, we didn’t suspect it would be accomplished with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to ethics.”
Former Khmer Rouge fighters forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with degraded, low-quality concrete walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School referred to the man who built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader; and he cared about his people,” said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, longstanding loyalty to Anlong Veng is finally challenged.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum enabled victims to publicly face the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly headed by the United Nations, delivered its first sentence against a former member of the Khmer Rouge, sentenced to 35 years in prison the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch".
Faced with this situation, anxiety has increased among the former Khmer Rouge fighters of Anlong Veng; complicates reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of Cambodia’s Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
“The situation creates divisions within families.”
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overcrowding.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia’s border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla guerrillas from their base located in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had held up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most former Khmer Rouge fighters have sunk into the black misery common to rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although some Khmer Rouge elite officers have retained their positions as local leaders in exchange for dropping their weapons, these are low-ranking, unskilled farmers.
"These people have benefited from very little follow-up after the capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are soaked in the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime."
“They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice grower.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok feeds everyone."
But now, life is difficult because we have to support our own needs.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge court has also caused concerns here.
The court is expected to begin the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, early next year.
The court's mandate is to prosecute senior leaders and key perpetrators of the crimes, but it did not say whether it was prosecuting beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation turned to Im Chaem, 64, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province under the Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodian Documentation Centre that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers were reportedly killed.
Recently, during a hectic evening, Im Chaem was returning from work in the field near his wooden house on pilotis, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia has to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang, from the documentation center.
"The reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces," he said.
“We need to put these pieces together so we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
He distributed it to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's history manuals, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the youth of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's links to the regime.
Touch Valeak, a 19-year-old student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new manual helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he returned home with the book to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court,” he says.
“They are suspicious because they don’t know exactly how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retains a powerful attraction here.
In the heights of the Dangrek Mountains, a path, overrun with weeds and sprinkled with plastic bags, leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a roof of rusty sheet metal.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, a 31-year-old mobile phone saleswoman on the roadside, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated at that place.
“But he has a great spirit, and many people go there to pray,” she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day she planned to walk to Pol Pot's last resting place where she would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in hopes of bringing luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its military-grade uranium stockpile
The Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, an essential component of nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of President Obama's campaign to secure nuclear materials worldwide.
