On the contrary, it is another constraint on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which collides with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits from the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems from science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, nearly 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal rigor, fines to the countries that violate them, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and it has long been defined, therefore now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were boosting deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany thought we should do (fiscal rigor and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow of the Central European country was when Merkel hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
Since then it has been subjected to fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published one were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, albeit slightly sweetened, has been approved and in the coming months we should be witnessing the process of reforming the Union that will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date on the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that violate the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare themselves in arrears and, in that case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany signals to us that we must follow a strict path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be a pity not to hear it.
It is not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we're being asked for is much harder.
And what he should absolutely not do in these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring us greater tranquillity.
And that we know how to seize the opportunity that was given to us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel’s criticism, the way has been paved for the thesis that it is necessary to put order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
And one of the possibilities envisaged cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too overcrowded with unserious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had warned us.
Sport and Fraud of the Law
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the willingness to escape a penalty.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has cast a lot of ink on the anti-sportive character of such behavior and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before the game ended (which their team was already clearly winning), the two players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes in determining the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of his group, the two players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the dam match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cartons to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee sanctioned with two matches the coach of the team, José Mourinho and different economic sums to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather a common one in the world of football.
It is so prevalent that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that this was provoked by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem displays the nobility and honor and on past occasions has condemned to a fine to its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization of his orchestrated, seemingly un-spoiled, histories.
In any case, the debate asks whether this kind of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulations, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e., whether these actions constitute a fraud of the law, since they are actions that respect the regulations of sport but seem to evade their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the correct gameplay is to prevent the team of offenders from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action has precisely tried to avoid the possibility of avoiding it.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is the type of benefit that offenders receive from the deliberate wrongdoings examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same game either, because obviously the result of the action assumes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club could not count on these players.
Obviously the advantage lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated all of a sudden and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move to the second round of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder, it is not so clear that this is an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which is still part of the making of strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they rather chose the moment at which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without breaking the penalty or escaping it.
Even though the line between genius and fraud of the law is widespread, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way to transmit the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
