A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
The United Nations today proposed in Cancun a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that corresponds to nearly one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of major concrete projects that the UN hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorescent bulbs or, better yet, by fluorescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be emitted by humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of the global car fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to raise global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But another 5 Gt will have to be subtracted from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade by 2020 in order to avoid it becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy need is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - this company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all-new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have made reservations about fluorescent bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion to build.
