Avengers Hackers and Spies in Diligence
The WikiLeaks case has double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that only appears as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file constituted by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits only report what could be read in any newspaper for months (except those Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi’s sinisterly cartoon profile has long been for sketch-based cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of news already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor knows where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who reconfirm what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, as I know, editor at Libération), who retain as true only what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as Newsweek was publishing the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make such a lot of noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultured person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into a center.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims in crisis as much as the “crazy”.
But let’s get to the deeper nature of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, any power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had fully proved itself since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the motorway borrowed, and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowing about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s power to reveal all secrets meant empty.
WikiLeaks has done nothing wrong to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put online any reserved information - this would be to publish it on a sticker on the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction falls within science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents moving discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, being carriers only of messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding such information in the rakes.
The information will be kept in single copies in locked drawers: at the bottom, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in the crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired telegraph (telephones).
Video cassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow them to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travel it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not surprising that the policy and communication techniques are back to horse cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on inside the embassies.
Now it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information to the press.
Climate: How France keeps its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the compliance with the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (so-called fast start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the great French bivouacs are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU took the big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, major side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has committed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional" in order to ensure that additional effort is made without being at the expense of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the funding of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of ODA.
Concretely, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, consider that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed equals 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> given.
Obviously, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given a loan... At most, the equivalent of interest should be counted only for the cost of commitment.
But France has to make such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the EU to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other countries) meet their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts 1 euro to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice turn of pass!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, she manages to make it appear that she is spending 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy did the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter on early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting system for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister for the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
