The score is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens, and five as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our investigation shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, is expected to be an encas by the study, and has traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were stuffed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most “rich” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt from it.
